<i> when I was looking for
 humpback chub,</i>

00:14:26.164 --> 00:14:30.202
<i> wouldn't leave me alone,
 they'll have water too.</i>

00:14:30.202 --> 00:14:34.440
<i> The Gila River downstream,
 this was taken in 1936.</i>

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.743
<i> One of the last tributaries
 of the Colorado.</i>

00:14:37.743 --> 00:14:38.810
<i> That's today.</i>

00:14:38.810 --> 00:14:40.546
<i> That was taken
 by my friend Jon Waterman,</i>

00:14:40.546 --> 00:14:44.316
<i> who paddled the length
 of the Colorado River.</i>

00:14:44.316 --> 00:14:47.018
<i> And then we come back down
 into Yuma, Arizona,</i>

00:14:47.018 --> 00:14:48.486
<i> right before
 the Colorado River crosses</i>

00:14:48.486 --> 00:14:50.823
<i> over the
 US-Mexican border.</i>

00:14:50.823 --> 00:14:53.224
<i> A massive amount of
 lettuce production here,</i>

00:14:53.224 --> 00:14:55.260
<i> agriculture throughout
 the region, and so</i>

00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:57.095
<i> if you are sitting there
 saying,</i>

00:14:57.095 --> 00:14:58.930
'This is interesting, Pete,
Colorado river is beautiful

00:14:58.930 --> 00:15:00.666
maybe I'll go raft it one day.

00:15:00.666 --> 00:15:02.467
But I mean, come on,
I've got plenty of water here

00:15:02.467 --> 00:15:05.537
in Washington D.C.,
why does this concern me?'

